The research design deliberately maximizes ideological and stylistic contrast between McCain's gracious, institution-affirming concession speech and Sanders' passionate, system-critical populist address. This provides a robust test for the framework's ability to differentiate between distinct political character signatures.

## EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

This report validates the Character Assessment Framework (CAF) v6.0 and its JSON-first architecture by analyzing the distinct character profiles of John McCain (Conservative-Institutional) and Bernie Sanders (Progressive-Populist). The analysis confirms all three primary research hypotheses.

**Hypothesis 1 (Ideological Differences)** was strongly supported. The framework identified two divergent character signatures: McCain‚Äôs rhetoric scored high on virtues like **Dignity (0.85)** and **Hope (0.80)**, exemplified by his calls for unity and respect for the democratic process [2, 7]. In contrast, Sanders‚Äô speech scored significantly higher on vices like **Tribalism (0.60)** and **Resentment (0.50)**, driven by a narrative of economic grievance against an oligarchy [5, 9].

**Hypothesis 2 (Coherence Differences)** was also supported. The Moral Character Strategic Contradiction Index (MC-SCI) successfully differentiated the two styles. McCain‚Äôs highly coherent, virtue-dominant speech yielded a very low **MC-SCI of 0.048**, indicating minimal character tension. Sanders' speech, which blended strong appeals to Justice with high levels of Resentment, produced a higher **MC-SCI of 0.073**, quantifying its greater internal contradiction.

Finally, **Hypothesis 3 (Architecture Validation)** was confirmed. The v6.0 pipeline successfully processed the two-document corpus, calculated all derived metrics, and enabled this synthesis without coordination failures, validating the robustness of the JSON-first architecture.

